Type of Data Needed: Structured data i.e. data in tabular form
Input features: Customer Information, Policy Information, Claim Information, Behavioral features, external verification data
Target variable or lable: 0 - Genuine claim; 1- fraudulent claim
Data collection method: Claims Submission Systems, Internal Insurance Databases, Third Party Sources, 
Data Quality Risks: Missinf data, imbalanced data,incorrect labels, duplicate records, noisy data
evolving fraud patterns, privacy and security risks

Suitable model or achitecture: Feed-Forward Neural Network
Reason:
A Feed-Forward Neural Network is the most suitable architecture for insurance claim fraud detection because the problem 
mainly uses structured tabular data and requires binary classification of fraudulent vs genuine claims.
Evaluation Plan:
The insurance claim fraud detection solution should be evaluated using both technical AI metrics and business performance 
metrics to ensure the model is accurate, reliable, and useful in real-world insurance operations.
Evaluation Plan:
1. Objective
Evaluate the AI-based fraud detection system to ensure it:
a.) accurately detects fraudulent claims
b.) minimizes false fraud alerts
c.) improves operational efficiency
d.)reduces financial losses
e.) supports human investigators effectively
2. Evaluation Scope

The evaluation will measure:
i.) Area	Purpose
ii) Technical Performance	Assess prediction quality
iii) Business Impact	Measure operational benefits
iv) Reliability	Identify failure risks
v) Human Validation	Ensure trustworthy decisions
3. Dataset Evaluation Strategy
Data Split
The dataset will be divided into:
Dataset	Percentage
Training Set	70%
Validation Set	15%
Testing Set	15%
Purpose:
Training → model learning
Validation → hyperparameter tuning
Testing → final unbiased evaluation
4. Technical Evaluation Metrics
4.1 Accuracy
Measures overall correct predictions.
Accuracy=
TP+TN+FP+FN
TP+TN	
Goal:
high overall prediction accuracy
4.2 Precision
Measures how many flagged fraud claims are actually fraudulent.
Precision=
TP+FP
Importance:
reduces false fraud accusations
Target:
high precision
4.3 Recall (Most Important)
Measures how many actual fraud cases are detected.
Recall=
TP+FN
Importance:
missing fraud cases is costly
Target:
maximize recall
4.4 F1-Score
Balances precision and recall.
F1=2×
Precision+Recall
Precision×Recall
Used because:
fraud datasets are imbalanced
4.5 Confusion Matrix
Analyzes:
correct fraud detection
missed fraud cases
false alerts
4.6 ROC-AUC Score
Measures fraud detection capability across thresholds.
Target:
AUC close to 1
5. Business Evaluation Metrics
5.1 Fraud Detection Rate
Percentage of fraudulent claims successfully identified.
5.2 Financial Loss Reduction
Measure reduction in fraud-related payouts.
Example:
savings after AI deployment
5.3 Claim Processing Time
Compare:
manual review time
AI-assisted review time
Goal:
faster claim handling
5.4 Investigator Productivity
Measure:
number of claims reviewed per day
investigation efficiency
5.5 False Investigation Rate
Monitor:
genuine customers incorrectly flagged
Goal:
minimize customer inconvenience
6. Human Review & Validation Process
Step 1: AI Fraud Prediction
AI assigns:
fraud probability score
Step 2: Suspicious Claim Flagging
High-risk claims are:
forwarded to investigators
Step 3: Human Investigation
Experts review:
documents
claim history
evidence
customer details
Step 4: Final Decision
Human investigators:
approve
reject
request more evidence
AI supports decisions but does not fully replace humans.
7. Possible Failure Cases
Failure Case	Risk
False Positives	Genuine claims flagged as fraud
False Negatives	Fraudulent claims missed
Data Imbalance	Model biased toward genuine claims
Evolving Fraud Patterns	New fraud methods undetected
Poor Data Quality	Incorrect predictions
Biased Historical Data	Unfair fraud detection
8. Risk Mitigation Strategies
Risk	Mitigation
Class imbalance	SMOTE / weighted loss
Overfitting	Regularization & validation
Data drift	Periodic retraining
False positives	Human review system
Noisy data	Data cleaning & validation
9. Monitoring After Deployment
The deployed system should continuously monitor:
fraud trends
prediction accuracy
false alert rates
investigator feedback
Model retraining should occur periodically.
10. Success Criteria
The solution is considered successful if it:
detects high percentage of fraud cases
reduces fraud-related losses
improves claim processing speed
maintains acceptable false positive rates
supports investigators efficiently
11. Final Workflow
Claim Submission
→ AI Fraud Scoring
→ Suspicious Claim Detection
→ Human Investigation
→ Final Claim Decision
12. Final Conclusion
The evaluation plan combines:
technical AI metrics
operational business impact
human validation
continuous monitoring

to ensure the fraud detection system is accurate, reliable, fair, and effective in real-world insurance operations
